   <title>Tutor</title>
   <content>
      <p>Here again is the probability distribution of
         Y<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T153320-0500"?>&#8212;<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T153318-0500" content=", "?>the
         number of defective parts in an hour in Yves' production line:</p>
      <image src="../webcontent/dig003.gif"/>
   </content>
   <question id="q1">
      <body>
         <p>Which of the following expressions represents the standard deviation of Y?</p>
         <image src="../../webcontent/flash/_u4_m3_digtutor5a_image1.gif"/>
      </body>
      <multiple_choice shuffle="false">
         <choice value="Res1">A</choice>
         <choice value="Res2">B</choice>
         <choice value="Res3">C</choice>
         <choice value="Res4">D</choice>
      </multiple_choice>
      <part>
         <response match="Res1" score="0">
            <feedback>Incorrect.  You are confusing values and probabilities. To calculate standard deviation, we look at the squared deviation between the values of X and its mean, 
               and weigh each of those deviations by the corresponding probability.  Also, you have used a mean of 2, instead of 2.7.  Please try again.</feedback>
         </response>
         <response match="Res2" score="10">
            <feedback>Good
               <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T153854-0500"?>j<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T153854-0500" content="J"?>ob!</feedback>
         </response>
         <response match="Res3" score="0">
            <feedback>Incorrect. Your mistake is that you are averaging the squared
               deviations twice. First you multiply each one by the corresponding weight
               (probability), which is the right thing to do, but then dividing again by 5<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T153908-0500"?>
               <?oxy_insert_end?>-<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T153909-0500"?>
               <?oxy_insert_end?>1 is wrong. You might be confusing the standard deviation of a
               random variable with
               the<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T154124-0500" content=" the"?>
               formula for
               s<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T153919-0500"?>&#8212;<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T153917-0500" content=" - "?>the
               sample standard
               deviation<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T153937-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
               which we introduced in the
               E<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T153940-0500"?>xploratory
               <?oxy_insert_end?>D<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T153944-0500"?>ata
               <?oxy_insert_end?>A<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T153948-0500"?>nalysis<?oxy_insert_end?>
               unit. Please try again.</feedback>
         </response>
         <response match="Res4" score="0">
            <feedback>Incorrect. You are almost right, though. Your choice just
               considers the
               deviations<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T154057-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
               instead of the squared deviations, as it should. Please try again.</feedback>
         </response>
      </part>
   </question>
